            <section class="mt-10 prose">
              <h2>How this Canada income tax calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool estimates your 2024 Canadian income tax and net pay by
                applying the current federal and provincial tax brackets, plus
                standard payroll deductions. It is designed for quick planning
                and education, not for filing your return.
              </p>

              <h3>1. Taxable income</h3>
              <p>
                We start from your employment income and other taxable income,
                then subtract RRSP contributions to get your
                <strong>taxable income</strong>:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                \( \text{Taxable income} = \text{Employment income} +
                \text{Other income} - \text{RRSP contributions} \)
              </div>

              <h3>2. Federal tax (2024 brackets)</h3>
              <p>
                For 2024, the federal tax brackets for individuals are
                approximately:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>15% on the first $55,867 of taxable income</li>
                <li>20.5% on the portion from $55,867 to $111,733</li>
                <li>26% on the portion from $111,733 to $173,205</li>
                <li>29% on the portion from $173,205 to $246,752</li>
                <li>33% on the portion over $246,752</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                The calculator applies these marginal rates to each slice of
                your income.
              </p>

              <h3>3. Provincial and territorial tax</h3>
              <p>
                Each province and territory has its own progressive tax brackets
                and basic personal amount. We use 2024 schedules for:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Alberta, British Columbia, Manitoba, New Brunswick,
                  Newfoundland and Labrador
                </li>
                <li>
                  Nova Scotia, Ontario, Prince Edward Island, Saskatchewan,
                  Yukon
                </li>
                <li>
                  Northwest Territories, Nunavut, and an approximate schedule
                  for Quebec
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>4. Non‑refundable tax credits</h3>
              <p>
                Canada uses <em>non‑refundable</em> tax credits to reduce your
                tax owing. This calculator includes:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Federal basic personal amount</li>
                <li>Provincial basic personal amount</li>
                <li>
                  Federal and provincial credits for CPP/QPP and EI/QPIP
                  contributions
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>The general formula is:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                \( \text{Net tax} = \text{Gross tax} - \sum (\text{Credit base}
                \times \text{Credit rate}) \)
              </div>

              <h3>5. CPP/QPP and EI/QPIP</h3>
              <p>If you choose to include payroll deductions, we estimate:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>CPP/QPP</strong> contributions on employment income
                  between the yearly basic exemption and the maximum pensionable
                  earnings.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>EI/QPIP</strong> premiums on insurable earnings up to
                  the annual maximum.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                These are then subtracted from your gross income to give your
                <strong>net take‑home pay</strong>.
              </p>

              <h2>Limitations and assumptions</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>Assumes one income earner and standard credits only.</li>
                <li>
                  Does not handle complex situations (self‑employment, capital
                  gains, dividends, rental income, etc.).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Quebec calculations are approximate and do not replace Revenu
                  Québec tools.
                </li>
                <li>
                  RRSP deduction is applied directly against taxable income, up
                  to the amount you enter.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                For official rates and detailed rules, always refer to the
                Canada Revenue Agency (CRA) and your provincial/territorial tax
                authority.
              </p>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

              <h3>Is Canada’s tax system progressive?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes. Both federal and provincial income taxes use progressive
                brackets. Only the income that falls into a higher bracket is
                taxed at that higher rate.
              </p>

              <h3>
                What is the difference between marginal and average tax rate?
              </h3>
              <p>
                Your <strong>marginal rate</strong> is the rate on your next
                dollar of income. Your
                <strong>average (effective) rate</strong> is total tax divided
                by your total income. The calculator shows your effective rate;
                your marginal rate will usually be higher.
              </p>

              <h3>How do RRSP contributions reduce my tax?</h3>
              <p>
                RRSP contributions are deducted from your income before tax is
                calculated. The tax savings are roughly your
                <em>marginal tax rate</em> multiplied by the RRSP amount.
              </p>

              <h3>Can I use this for tax filing?</h3>
              <p>
                No. This is an educational estimator. For filing, use certified
                tax software or work with a CPA or other qualified tax
                professional.
              </p>
